description:
Hugh has both commerce and law degrees from The University of Western Australia. Hugh was admitted as a legal practitioner in Western Australia in December 1989.

His principal areas of legal practice are property law, wills and estate planning, business succession planning, general commercial law and the law relating to Retirement Villages and Aged Care. Hugh's property law practice focuses on leasing (commercial, retail and industrial) and property developments. He also has extensive experience in wills and estate planning for individuals; and business succession  planning. Hugh also presented to the Institute of Chartered Accountants and Centrelink on succession planning and wills.

Hugh is a fellow of the Taxation Institute of Australia and a member of the Australian Institute of Company Directors. For almost 14 years he was a member of the Board of Southern Cross Care WA (Inc), a not-for-profit organisation which is a major provider of aged care services in Western Australia. From November 2005 until December 2009 he held the position as Chairman of the Board of Directors.

Hugh has tutored and lectured at The University of Western Australia, University of Notre Dame and the Securities Institute of Australia in areas ranging from property law, corporations law, finance law and succession law. He has also presented to the Australian Society of Certified Practising Accountants on corporate governance for not-for-profit organisations.

description:
Pragma (www.pragmalegal.com.au) helps its clients avoid and resolve disputes efficiently so they can spend time on more important things.

Pragma was recently recognised as one of the fastest growing law firms in Australia (Australasian Lawyer Magazine, October, 2016), we were nominated as a finalist in the Australian Law Awards and are listed in Australasian Lawyer Innovative Firms for 2016.  
 
I am a graduate of the University of Western Australia.

I was admitted to practice in the Supreme Court of Western Australia in 2008 and in the High Court of Australia in 2009. I regularly appear as an advocate in all Courts and Tribunals.

I completed my articles of clerkship with a commercial law firm before spending 5½ years at a major international law firm in its Litigation and Dispute Resolution Division. During that time I was promoted to Senior Associate.  I spent 18 months working in the firm's Melbourne office.

I have lectured to law and business students at tertiary level.  I give presentations to members of the legal profession through the Piddington Society (www.piddingtonsociety.com) and other legal education providers like LexisNexis and Legalwise.

I hold a Masters of Laws from the University of Western Australia.   I also sit on the Courts Committee of the Law Society of Western Australia.

I am a committee member of The Piddington Society (www.piddingtonsociety,com) – an organisation which promotes access to justice and legal education.

In 2017, I founded the Subiaco Community Legal Service (www.subiaco.legal). I sit on the Service's Board as Chair.

I have a keen interest in innovation and the law.  Please feel free to contact me on (08) 6188 3341 or aaron.mcdonald@pragmalegal.com.au

description:
Elle Nikou Madalin practices in a broad range of commercial, common law and public law matters. She has experience in all Victorian and Federal jurisdictions, including in the High Court of Australia.

Elle has advised and appeared in complex trial, appeal and interlocutory matters representing corporations, public bodies and private individuals. Elle has also represented the State of Victoria numerous times, as well as having acted for local councils and other government and political entities. 

In addition to her broad corporate and commercial experience, Elle has special experience in defamation and business reputation matters, including injurious falsehood and misleading and deceptive conduct claims. She regularly advises and appears on behalf of both plaintiffs and defendants in matters concerning both online and print publications. Elle has also been a lecturer in Defamation at the Australian Catholic University. 

Elle also has special expertise in sports law, including doping and disciplinary matters - both as counsel assisting the tribunal and for the athlete themselves. In the past, Elle sat as a member of FFV's Disciplinary Tribunal in both its appellate and original jurisdiction (including, frequently, as Chair). Elle has also recently sat as Chair of Disciplinary Tribunals for both Swimming Victoria and Hockey Victoria.

From time to time Elle is invited to teach and present at universities accross Victoria. She also accepts various public speaking and lecturing engagements, including having presented at the Australian Women in Law Leadership Summit.

Elle's key areas of practice include:

- Competition & Consumer Protection
- Contracts
- Corporations Law
- Equity & Trusts
- Defamation
- Intellectual Property
- Industrial & Employment
- Partnership Disputes
- Public & Administrative Law
- Restraint of Trade
- Securities & Investments

description:
Div is a strategic champion of diversity and inclusion.  As CEO and Co-Founder she shows that there is a business imperative to cultural inclusion - MindTribes works with Australian and MNC's to culturally align staff and tracks performance improvement across 12 months.  Div is also the Co-Founder of CDW (Culturally Diverse Women) a social enterprise working to advance culturally different corporate women.  Div has a personal touchpoint with this both struggling and thriving with her cultural and gender diversity.  

Prior to founding she spent 14 years in People and Culture roles in the BPO industry working across South Africa, Malaysia, Australia, India and The Philippines.  She has authentically and successfully transformed her brand from a senior employee to a CEO and Co-Founder of a business that has gone from idea to execution to commercialisation.  She also has a strong social justice approach, giving 10% of revenue to Plan International's Because I am a Girl campaign.  MindTribes is a Plan International Ambassador.

Her most recent appointment to the Board of STREAT is a culmination of her passion for youth, access to food, employability and the large number of refugees and migrants who find themselves in this plight. 

MindTribes. Connecting Cultures. Aligning Performance
jobDescription:
MindTribes. Connecting Cultures. Aligning Performance.  

MindTribes works with both Australian and Multinational corporates to improve business results by culturally aligning staff to internal and external customers, team members and stakeholders.   This means working from a job centric view to accelerate competence when working in a foreign climate.  We ask the question, what do you need to do differently to buy, sell, service, negotiate and manage in a culturally different environment?  We have found that corporates who don’t invest in growing cultural competence suffer unrealised sales, low customer satisfaction metrics, staff turnover and poor integration.

Our differentiator is that we don’t just focus on cultural training.  We focus on operational and business performance when two or more foreign climates come together.  There is no other company that can track business improvement through cultural alignment.  

Our markets are offshored contact centres, shared services and inbound expatriates.   We have been recognised as a Telstra Business Award Finalist (Vic), 2016 and Contact Centre Excellence Awards Runner up and Honorary mention, 2017 for Best Improvement Project.
jobDescription2: Working with a talented Board team to support STREAT's mission and execute on the CEO and Founders vision.  STREAT works to stop youth homelessness and disadvantage, one mouthful at a time. Together the team offer disadvantaged youth aged 16-25 a supported pathway from the street to a sustainable livelihood.  23% of these youth are CALD, which is where my passion lies.

schoolDescription: Master of science in mathematical modelling and scientific computing.This intensive one-year masters course included a wide range of topics in applied mathematics, mathematical modelling, probabilistic modelling, and scientific computing. The course was highly collaborative in nature, and focussed on the communication of mathematical ideas and the coherent formulation of mathematical problems from ambiguous problem descriptions.There was also a substantial research component, which provided me the opportunity to write five papers on topics of my choosing. The course culminated in a research dissertation.Dissertation title: Accelerating Optimisation Algorithms.My dissertation was on the acceleration of first-order optimisation algorithms. The motivation for this research is large-scale machine learning and data science applications. In my dissertation I proposed new acceleration algorithms that perform very competitively with state-of-the-art acceleration methods.

description:
I am an environmental lawyer with over 25 years’ experience in legal study, practice and research, in Australia and the Indo-Pacific. I am committed to working collaboratively across disciplines, to translate law and policy into tangible and positive outcomes. 

As Director of the University of Western Australia (UWA) Oceans Institute, and Dean of Law before that, I provided strategic leadership and management, direction and co-ordination of academic strategy, as well as management and prioritisation of resources and infrastructure, to ensure innovation, cohesion and sustainability. 

I specialise in international and comparative environmental law. My particular expertise lies in issues related to marine environmental governance, heritage law, sustainable development and community-based marine management in small island states. I have published and presented widely in these areas including over 50 publications. 

Prior to joining UWA I held a variety of academic positions including as Director of the Centre for International & Environmental Law and Co-Director of the Centre for Climate Futures at Macquarie University. I have been managing director of a litigation support company, and later practised as a barrister in Sydney for over seven years, largely in the area of common law.

I was admitted to practice in the Supreme Court of WA on 2 April 2009. 

I became an Associate of Carr & Co in 2010.

I was admitted to practice in the High Court of Australia on 11 July 2011. 

I was appointed a Director of Carr & Co on 1 December 2012.

I was nominated for the Family Law Practitioners’ Association Young Lawyer of the Year award in 2014.

I successfully completed a Master of Applied Law (Family Law) and obtained an LL.M (Master of Laws) through the College of Law Australia in 2014.

I specialise in the management of complicated financial and parenting matters in the Family Court. I have a particular interest in “big money cases”, which usually involve complex trust and corporate structures and taxation and accounting issues.

I have appeared as instructing solicitor and junior counsel in many complex children's and financial cases both in the Family Court of WA and in the Full Court of the Family Court, a number of which, are now reported cases.  

I also appeared as junior counsel with Hon Peter Dowding SC in

1. an appeal to the Full Court of the Family Court reported as Stanford v Stanford (2011) FLC 93-483 & Stanford v Stanford (2012) FLC ¶93-495; 

2. a successful special leave application to the High Court (Stanford v Stanford [2012] HCA Trans 154 (22 June 2012));

3. a successful appeal in the High Court reported as Stanford v Stanford [2012] HCA 52; and

4. a successful application made pursuant to the Bankruptcy Act 1966 (Cth) to set aside an insolvency notice, which had been cross-vested from the Federal Court of Australia to the Family Court reported as Beaman and Bond [2014] FCWA 21.

description:
Robyn is Professor of Law at the UWA Law School where she teaches and researches contract, remedies, mediation and family law and co-convenes the UWA Law School Obligations Hub. Robyn is a leading international authority on the role of apologies in private law and dispute resolution.  In 2013 she co-founded the International Network for Law and Apology Research. She was invited by the Hong Kong Department of Justice in 2014 to write a research report on the enactment of apology legislation in Hong Kong. 

Robyn researches and publishes in articles and book chapters on these and other areas of private and dispute resolution. She is also editor of Civil Remedies: Issues and Developments (Federation Press, 1996); The Place of Apology in the Law with Professor Prue Vines in the Oñati Socio-Legal Series (2017) and most recently, Carroll, Chiu and Vines Apology Ordinance: commentary and annotations (Sweet & Maxwell, Hong Kong, 2018).  

Robyn's teaching and research interests in Family Law and Elder Law include elder mediation, property and financial issues for aging Australians and their families, prevention of elder abuse, and the significance of family violence in family law property matters.

Robyn took up the elected position of Deputy Chair of Academic Board at UWA from January 2017- December 2018 and is a member of the Steering Committee of Academic Board and Academic Council.

description:
I practised as a solicitor from 1984 till 1995 and then as a barrister till my retirement from legal practice altogether in June 2013. Since January 2010 I have lectured at Edith Cowan University, teaching Contract Law, Remedies and Legal Process though I remained at the bar and maintained my membership of Francis Burt Chambers as a door tenant. In June 2013, I decided that I would retire from legal practice altogether. Some of my friends thought I was too young to retire but I think they were just envious. Since June 2013, I have devoted my time and energy entirely to life in academia and whilst at times I miss the Bar, I wholeheartedly love the whole academic lifestyle, which imposes different demands and also provides tremendous satisfaction and fulfilment.

Whilst I was at the bar, I practised in commercial litigation, and took instructions mainly in contract, property and trade practices disputes, and also did quite a lot of work in general tort and succession. 

I teach contract law, property (in conjunction with remedies), and the legal process.

My particular passion is for the teaching of legal logic, which I teach as part of my legal process unit

Together with my good friend and co author Anibeth Desierto,I have just written a textbook for LexisNexis Butterworths entitled: Legal Problem Solving and Syllogistic Analysis: A Guide for Foundation Law Students. It went to print on 29 September 2016.

Fuller details are in my description of "lecturer in law' below.

description:
Consultancy:  

Mark is available to undertake consultancy in higher education policy and practice, research ethics and research integrity. He has acted as a consultant to various institutions and agencies, including the Federal, NSW, Queensland and SA Governments, CSIRO and the NHMRC, the European Research Council, and on educational matters to higher education institutions in Australia, Hong Kong, New Zealand, Taiwan and the United Kingdom. He is or has been a Discipline Scholar and Fellow of the Australian Learning and Teaching Council, a Fellow of the Australian College of Educators, a Principal Fellow of the Higher Education Academy in the United Kingdom, a Fellow of the Academy of Social Sciences, a Fellow of the Royal Society for the Arts and a member of the SACE Board of South Australia.

Research 

Mark has published in the areas of: criminology, research ethics and integrity, higher education policy and practice, and racism. 

He is author of South African Political Exile in the United Kingdom (Palgrave Macmillan, 1999), Ethics and the Governance of Criminological Research in Australia (NSW Government, 2004) and Research Ethics and Integrity for Social Scientists: Beyond Regulatory Compliance (Sage, 2015), co-author (with Iain Hay) of Research Ethics for Social Scientists: Between Ethical Conduct and Regulatory Compliance (Sage, 2006) and co-editor of International Victimology (Australian Institute of Criminology, 1996), Criminal Justice in Diverse Communities (Federation, 2000), Crime and Justice in Australia (Lawbook Company, 2003), and Crime and Justice: a Guide to Criminology (Lawbook Company, 2006). 

Teaching 

Between 1988 and 1992, he lectured in the United Kingdom. He moved to Flinders University in 1993 and was Winthrop Professor at the University of Western Australia from 2010-16. 

Specialities: criminology, socio-legal studies, social science research ethics and integrity, learning and teaching in higher education, higher education governance

description:
I am a corporate and commercial lawyer at Jackson McDonald.

My primary areas of practice include equity capital markets, corporate advisory, mergers and acquisitions (regulated and unregulated) and commercial contracts.

I have acted for public and private companies on a variety of transactions including initial public offerings, backdoor listings, capital raisings (including rights issues, security purchase plans and private placements) and mergers and acquisitions (including share sales, asset sales and schemes of arrangement). I regularly advise on matters such as corporate structuring, continuous disclosure, due diligence, prospectus preparation, regulatory compliance, statutory interpretation, corporate governance, directors’ duties and commercial transactions generally. 

I am experienced in drafting a wide range of corporate and commercial documents including commercial agreements (such as shareholder, services, joint venture, sale and purchase, employment, non-disclosure and escrow agreements), employee incentive plans, constitutions, ASX announcements and notices of meeting. I have also prepared applications to the Australian Securities & Investments Commission, Australian Securities Exchange, Foreign Investment Review Board and Takeovers Panel.

I regularly present accredited continuing professional development (CPD) seminars, including on topics such as An Introduction to Sale of Business Transactions, Privately Held Businesses: Common Legal Issues, Changes to the Laws Governing Incorporated Associations and An Introduction to Insolvency.

My qualifications include a Bachelor of Laws (Distinction), a Bachelor of Arts (Political and International Studies) and a Graduate Diploma of Legal Practice. 

I am admitted to practise in both the Supreme Court of Western Australia and the High Court of Australia, and I hold an unrestricted practising certificate.

description:
Lisa Maree is a young female global entrepreneur and Bondi Beach local.

Lisa has always loved swimwear and knew there was a demand for fashion-forward swimwear with a point of difference. She launched Lisa Maree in 2009, and is now selling to boutique and department stores across World including luxury E-tailer Net-a-Porter, Nordstrom, Harvey Nichols, Bloomingdales & Selfridges. At Glamazon we understand the importance of looking and feeling your best, whether that means weekly beauty maintenance or being perfectly polished for those special occasions. description:
Scott Farquhar is the co-founder and co-CEO of Atlassian, a collaboration software company that helps teams organize, discuss and complete shared work. More than 60,000 large and small organizations use Atlassian’s tracking, collaboration, communication, service management and development products to work smarter and deliver quality results on time.

Atlassian donates 1% of profit, product, equity and employee time to charity, helping thousands of children in developing countries receive an education. In 2011, Scott was awarded the Corporate Social Responsibility Award by the Young Presidents’ Organization (YPO). In 2015, Scott helped spearhead Pledge 1%, a corporate philanthropy movement dedicated to making the community a key stakeholder in every business. To date, more than 1,250 companies in more than 38 countries have joined the movement.

Scott was the youngest person ever to be awarded the ‘Australian Entrepreneur of the Year’ in 2006 by Ernst & Young alongside co-founder and co-CEO Mike Cannon-Brookes. He holds a Bachelor of Science in business information technology from the University of New South Wales, Australia.
jobDescription:

Our mission is to change the face of corporate philanthropy.

description:
Upon completion of high school I entered straight into the workforce, and after trying a few things I joined my family's 108-year-old business Winning Appliances. After a short time working in sales and deliveries, I saw an opportunity to sell appliances and whitegoods online. Some tough conversations with management at Winning Appliances followed, who weren't convinced about the potential power of selling goods online. Subsequently, I set up www.appliancesonline.com.au as a pure play online retailer in 2005. 

The learning curve has been exponential and we have cemented our position as an award-winning online retailer, providing a platform where Australians feel comfortable buying large one-off items online without setting foot into a physical store. Our business has grown to employ over 500 staff, with our head-office in Redfern, Sydney and warehouses established in most states. 
Appliances Online is now Australia’s largest online retailer of appliances, delivering to 95% of the population and stocking more brands than any other online appliance retailer. Between 2005 and 2014 more than 400,000 unique customers have purchased from our company. We have also embraced social media and our Facebook community is larger than 335,000 (and growing every day). I was very proud to since be asked by my family to take over the running of my family's business.

The main similarity between Appliances Online and Winning Appliances is that our aim is to impress every customer. We want to provide the customer with a fantastic experience so they come back to buy from us again and again. Our mission is to provide the best shopping experience in the world. Our strengths include online marketing, SEO, SEM, technology, distribution, sales, business development, innovation and extreme customer service. As the company grows so do my goals for what I want to be doing online and as such we have picked up and started a few complimentary customer experience focused businesses along the way.

      MARC is an independent, family owned and run, Australian luxury fashion brand.
jobDescription:
Established in 2003 by siblings Camilla Freeman-Topper and Marc Freeman, CAMILLA AND MARC is an independent, family owned and run, Australian luxury fashion brand. 

Celebrating 15 years of success since its high-profile launch at Australian Fashion Week in 2003, CAMILLA AND MARC has become the local star in luxury womenswear. With a sophisticated tone that reflects the ease of the Australian lifestyle, the brand has built a design ethos that is at once contemporary and effortlessly elegant. The key message of the brand is luxurious, high-end fashion for discerning consumers across signature product offerings: luxe party wear, classic tailoring and separates. C&M CAMILLA AND MARC- the brands second ready-to-wear line launched in 2012 as a part of a greater brand strategy to target a broader customer base. The collection is a youthful, price pointed offering encompassing a complete apparel offering alongside a selection of swimwear and denim. In 2018 the brand offering continues to expand with the launch of eyewear, leather handbags and kidswear.

A distinct and opulent design philosophy infiltrates every element of the business. 

Key to the role of Head of Marketing is to proactively grow the CAMILLA AND MARC brand, by clearly communicating and positioning the brand at the forefront of the Australian design category. The Head of Marketing is responsible for overseeing the Marketing function, developing marketing strategies and the execution of related tactics via digital, in-store POS, eCommerce, PR and Events in line with CAMILLA AND MARC’s business requirements. 

In conjunction with the Creative Director, CEO, and General Manager, the role develops commercial creative concepts to support all elements of Marketing communications across all channels. The role also works collaboratively with the Retail and Sales teams to ensure below the line marketing activities drive sales and traffic to CAMILLA AND MARC stores, stockists and e-boutique.

As a Marketing, PR & Brand Consultant, I joined the team at UMENCO as General Manager.

As leading specialists in human resources, organisational and leadership development, recruitment and executive search and career coaching, UMENCO strive to ensure you love your work. Based in both Australia and the USA, UMENCO clients span the globe, from Australia to North America and The United Kingdom. Championing positive and powerful partnerships within the global and local fashion industry, UMENCO’s holistic approach ensures each client collaboration results in shared discoveries of new and innovative creative landscapes.

"UMENCO strongly supports the connection between individuals and brands, empowering each of us to bring our very best selves to work," explains Angela Briggs, CEO of UMENCO.

UMENCO’s Human Resources strategies and leadership programmes in addition to their recruitment services will build your brands’ profile in the market place. A commitment to invest in your employee experience impacts engagement, performance and productivity. 

With the belief that HR is the new PR - it was my role and responsibility to work closely with CEO Angela Briggs on how to create and formalise the UMENCO brand blueprint and to elevate the company profile. 

By creating the all important brand piece - to first capture the essence of UMENCO (values, integrity, innovation and individualism) and to define the company DNA - we created the backbone of the brand and business which then formulated the content and communications plan across all channels.

description:
Sean is an experienced senior executive with a broad background in investment banking, principal investing, capital markets and treasury. Sean is a co-founder and Managing Partner of Treadstone Resource Partners, a boutique corporate advisory firm, working across Natural Resources, Healthcare and Technology.  In addition to Treadstone, he is involved with a number of young companies, assisting with their strategy and corporate development. Sean acts as an investor, board member, adviser and/or mentor. 

Sean spent 10 years at Goldman Sachs in Australia holding a number of senior positions including:
- Managing Director, Head of the Principal Investment Area (PIA) for Australia and New Zealand
- Managing Director, Head of Capital Products Group

As the MD for PIA in Australia and New Zealand, he was responsible for the Private Equity funds, Mezzanine Investment Funds and direct investments made by GS Australia, managing in excess of A$1bn in capital. After leaving GS, he is was retained by Goldman PIA in Australia as an advisor and continued as Chairman of the various Investment Committees of the PIA Funds until Dec 2013.

Sean's experience at GS also includes co-leading the firm’s efforts in the Capital Products business which incorporates GS's Australian debt capital markets, structured financing, leveraged finance and equity linked business. During this time he lead a team and was directly involved in some of the largest and most innovative financings for Australian corporates.

Prior to joining Goldman Sachs, Sean was Head of Structured Finance and Securitisation at SG Australia focusing on securitisation and asset financing. Sean had also previously held positions with Westpac Banking Corporation in Treasury and Institutional Banking, having commenced a career in finance with Citibank.

Before entering a career in finance, Sean was an officer in the Royal Australian Navy.

Sean holds a Bachelor of Arts from the University of New South Wales.

description:
Listen to Vince Luong’s backstory and you’ll soon understand why his work ethic and drive have made him a self-motivated entrepreneur. Vince’s parents came to Australia with nothing ready to build a new life after the Vietnam War. Growing up in this hardworking household, Vince and his nine siblings all follow paths of startups and entrepreneurship.

After completing a degree in banking and finance / international trade, he felt the pull of being his own boss and launched Allure Bathrooms, a retail bathroom supplier from his garage. While Allure’s beginnings were humble, in just four years the company now turns over $12 million a year, has 35 employees and four mega showrooms with plans to go franchise early next year. Vince’s second business, Nordik Living, is an online venture offering affordable Scandinavian style furniture to the masses.

As with any startup, it hasn’t been smooth sailing for Vince. He has experienced the frustration of being short on staff when demands were high. There’s no pause button for business, so Vince knows Weploy will offer recruitment solutions he and so many other employers are looking for.

When Vince isn’t busy running his three businesses, you’ll find him working on his car collection including a 1971 Datsun 240z or sharing business stories with his family around the dinner table.

By 2020, the Australian workforce will be comprised of 40% contingent staff, with a vast majority undertaking this mode of work by choice.

What is Weploy?
What we do is simple; We connect businesses to pre-vetted staff in under a minute. All Weployees complete 6 rounds of vetting, including psychometric, cognitive and personality profiling, before they are onboarded into our community.
Accessing this community means companies can solve efficiency problems to prioritise high-value tasks, innovate through technology enablement, and have agility around supply - the capacity to flex teams up and down based on business requirements.

What do I do?
I work closely with business leaders to unlock productivity blockers and enable them to execute on their strategies. Being able to focus 100% on mission-critical tasks and project elements increases productivity and drives better outcomes.

description:
I completed my PhD from the School of Computer Science and Engineering, UNSW in Machine Learning and Natural Language Processing (NLP) in August 2016. My research has a strong focus on applying Machined Learning techniques to Text Mining, and I’m especially interested in knowledge discovery from large-scale social networks where rich textual contents and complex social interactions co-exist, and in understanding how a synergetic approach leveraging both contents and link structures can facilitate the mining of knowledge. Statistical modelling and data analysis are also among my research interests.

I worked as a Data Scientist during my PhD candidature on two ARC-linkage projects in areas of Epidemiology and Criminology, with my main responsibilities covering data crunching, analysis and visualisation. This interdisciplinary research experience compliments my knowledge in Computer Science. The unique opportunity to collaborate with people from different fields with distinct patterns of thinking and ways of approaching problems helped me became a sharp thinker and a highly effective communicator. Besides my main responsibilities, I have also contributed to research designs and strategic decision makings.

In March 2015 I joined Macquarie Bank to work on a revolutionary initiative that aims to provide on-demand investment advice that is highly customised to each user's unique circumstances. Ten months later, this vision to democratise investment advice and make investing as uncomplicated as buying a meal became a reality — the much celebrated OwnersAdvisory platform.

With a strong academic background and extensive working experience in data science, my biggest passion is to enable humanity to harness the power of data through life-changing information products. I have been actively involved in data-centric technology startups and let’s connect if you share a similar passion.

description:
Launched in 2017, Spaceship is an Australian financial services company whose vision is to engage young people in actively building a strong and secure financial future. Spaceship uniquely leverages technology with the aim of removing friction, cost and complexity from the financial products it offers.

Spaceship offers managed fund products to Australian residents and is the promoter of the Spaceship superannuation product (currently issued by Tidswell Financial Services Ltd). Spaceship's superannuation product was released in January 2017 and now has over $228m in assets under management (AUM) (as at 30-Sep-2018).

Spaceship’s new Voyager product, released in April 2018, aims to help make investing in a diversified portfolio simple, convenient and affordable and is brought together in one beautifully designed app. With Voyager, customers can choose to invest in the Spaceship Index Portfolio, a low-cost market index fund, or the Spaceship Universe Portfolio, which is a portfolio of eligible securities carefully selected by Spaceship's investment team. Voyager has no minimum investment, no brokerage costs and is free for balances below $5,000. For balances above that, Voyager has total fees of between 0.05% to 0.10% per year. This means an investment of $10,000, held within a Spaceship Voyager managed fund for a year will cost between $2.50 to $5.00 in fees depending on portfolio selection. Spaceship’s Voyager has over 25,000 members and over $19.4m in AUM (as at 30-Sep-18) and is growing at over 200 members per day.

Spaceship has expanded to over 40 employees across engineering, operations, compliance, risk, marketing and investment and has over $20m of capital on its balance sheet to invest in its operation.

Spaceship has received significant financial backing from some of the world’s most renowned venture capitalists including Horizons Ventures, AirTree Ventures, Valar Ventures, Sequoia Capital and New Enterprise Associates.
